[2] Germany (mainland), Slovakia (suspected), others
Date: Wed 22 Feb 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Times Online, 21 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,25149-2050604,00.html>

Germany today reported 22 new cases of the deadly H5N1 strain of bird
flu. Till Backhaus, a German agriculture minister, said that he believed
that there was now a growing risk of H5N1 spreading to the country's
poultry farms.
The disease -- previously confined to the Baltic island of Ruegen --
has now been confirmed on the German mainland. A state of emergency
was declared in 2 districts of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania to allow
the army to be deployed for disease control measures.
"We do not have this in hand," Herr Backhaus told the AFP news agency.
When the EU veterinary experts last met, on 12 Dec 2005, H5N1 had yet
to reach the Continent. Cases have since been confirmed within the EU
in Austria, Germany, Greece, [Hungary], Italy, Slovenia and France,
although all so far have been confined to migratory wild birds rather
than domestic poultry flocks.
Meanwhile, Slovakia became the 8th EU country to report bird flu
after finding the H5 strain in a wild hawk [species not specified]
and a smew, a type of duck [a small Old World merganser (_Mergus
albellus_), picture at
<http://www.fsinet.or.jp/~bird/bird/photo/jpeg/mikoaisa.jpg>],
near its borders with Austria and Hungary. The dead birds have been
sent to the EU's special laboratory at Weybridge in Surrey for
further analysis to see whether it is H5N1.
[The CRL's website, updated on 21 Feb 2006, does not indicate the receipt of a
sample from Slovakia; see
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/corporate/vla/science/science-viral-ai-update.htm>.]
The Slovak authorities have set up a 3km exclusion zone and a 10km
surveillance zone around each of the sites, in accordance with EU
policy.
France, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Denmark, Greece, Luxembourg and
Sweden have already ordered farmers to bring their domestic poultry
indoors as a preventive measure to halt the spread of the disease.
In Britain, the Department for the Environment, Fisheries and Rural
Affairs (Defra) has said that bringing poultry indoors -- a move
which would stop farmers being able to sell the fowl as free-range
birds -- was not necessary until an outbreak was confirmed in the UK.
EU veterinary officials were today [21 Feb 2006] debating plans put
forward by France and the Netherlands to allow poultry to be given a
general flu vaccine. They need EU approval because of the trade
implications of vaccinating commercial poultry, as vaccination in
itself involves dosing birds with viral matter.
Some EU governments, including Britain, oppose vaccination because it could
mean the whole of Europe loses its "disease-free" status. They gave warning
that no vaccine is yet available directly to tackle the H5N1 strain and that
the more general vaccination holds no guarantees of curing the disease or
preventing its spread. "There is no bird flu in poultry in Britain, or in
poultry anywhere in the EU," said a British Government spokesman [he's already
out of date, see [1] Austria above - Mod.JW]. "But we are keeping vaccination
under urgent review, and we remain to be convinced that it is the right
solution."
A meeting of farm ministers in Brussels yesterday [20 Feb 2006] also
heard warnings that vaccination would be costly and logistically
difficult, since birds must be inoculated twice in a 3-week period.
A European Commission official confirmed there was no guarantee
vaccination would work and that the export status of a country which
had vaccinated its poultry would be in doubt.
He agreed that there was a gray area about the export status of a country
whose commercial poultry stock had been vaccinated, because, as in the case of
mad cow disease [sic; should read "Foot and mouth disease" -- there is no
vaccine for BSE], vaccination to counter the threat automatically costs a
country its official status as free of the disease.
"The vaccination request will be considered by the Standing Committee
on the Food Chain and Animal Health (today [21 Feb 2006]). But there
would always be a risk of the H5N1 strain of the virus going
undetected if it did enter a vaccinated poultry population," said the
Commission spokesman.
"In addition, the only vaccines available are those that can be
administered by injection, and certain categories of poultry might
need as many as 3 injections."
The meeting of veterinary officials is due to end at 5:30 p.m., and
conclusions will be published after that [see item 2].
Elsewhere in the world, health workers in western India today [21 Feb
2006] expanded a massive slaughter of chickens to contain reported
outbreaks of the H5N1 virus, while Malaysia began killing birds after
reporting its 1st case of the disease in more than a year.
Indonesia, meanwhile, was preparing to test thousands of chickens in
the capital, Jakarta, and Hong Kong's government said a dead magpie
found near an urban flower market was infected with the deadly strain.
5 regions of Nigeria are battling H5N1 in domestic poultry, and although the
country has yet to register its 1st human case of the disease, the World
Health Organization warned today [21 Feb 2006] that it could still easily
infect people. "There's really no time frame, because as long as the virus is
circulating, it could jump into humans," said Dick Thompson, a spokesman for
the UN health agency on infectious diseases.
[Byline: Jenny Booth]
--
