[3] France & Netherlands, vaccination - EU approval
Date: Wed 22 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU Press release IP/06/197, 21 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?
reference=IP/06/197&format=HTML>

Avian Influenza: France and Netherlands present vaccination plans for poultry
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
French and Dutch plans to carry out targeted preventive vaccination
campaigns on certain poultry as a precautionary measure against
highly pathogenic avian influenza have been presented to Member
States in the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health
(SCFCAH) today [21 Feb 2006]. The presentations were followed by
positive discussions in the Committee on the technical and scientific
details of the plans, as these are the 1st such vaccination programs
against the H5N1 virus to be proposed in the EU. On the basis of
today's discussions, the Commission will now consider proposals to
approve the plans and to lay down specific conditions that must be
met in applying them. The discussions will continue in the Committee
tomorrow morning [22 Feb 2006].
The Dutch plan entails vaccinating hobby poultry and free-range
laying hens throughout the whole country. The vaccination will be
provided on a voluntary basis, as an alternative to the requirement
that these birds be kept indoors.
The French plan foresees the vaccination of ducks and geese in the
departments of Landes, Loire-Atlantique and Vendee, which are
considered to be areas at high risk of avian influenza. The intention
is to begin vaccination immediately and continue until 1 Apr 2006,
during which time around 900 000 birds are expected to be immunized.
Both Member States outlined the monitoring and control measures that
would be followed with regard to the vaccinated birds. These include
the use of sentinel birds (i.e. unvaccinated control birds) to
monitor for an avian influenza outbreak in the vaccinated flock,
regular testing of the vaccinated and sentinel birds, and the
continued application of bio-security provisions already in place.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[On 22 Feb 2006, the above Dutch and French plans were, reportedly,
approved by the European Union animal health experts; see
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/BRU004380.htm>.
Though not mentioned, it may be assumed that the vaccine considered
will be an inactivated H5N2 (DIVA) vaccine. - Mod.AS]
