[4] Malaysia
Date: Wed 22 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NewStraightsTimes, 22 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/nst/Wednesday/Frontpage/20060222121530/Arti
cle/index_html>

Bird Flu Update: The quick, silent killer
-----------------------------------------
When his flock of 70 chickens started dying suddenly over a 10-day
period, retired soldier Sharip Ibrahim was mystified. Now he knows
they had been infected by the H5N1 virus.
Sharip, 66, who rears chickens to sell eggs at his home in Kampung
Pasir Wardieburn, Setapak, said today [22 Feb 2006]: "One day last
week, I went out in the morning, and when I returned home in the
afternoon I noticed some of the chickens were dead."
More chickens died over the following 2 days, and by this morning,
his entire flock of 70 chickens was gone.
"I buried the chickens at the back of my house. In the 40 years I
have been rearing chickens, nothing of this sort has ever happened,"
he said at his house. Sharip said he did not report the deaths to the
authorities, as he was not aware of the bird flu contagion. "It was
only when I saw the authorities going door-to-door collecting
chickens last night that I realized what had happened," he said.
Another villager, who wanted to be known only as Hashim, said his
flock of 12 chickens died within 2 days, a week after Chinese New
Year. "After I returned from my hometown after Chinese New Year, I
found my chickens dead in the coop," he said. Hashim, 69, said his
neighbor told him the chickens had died over 2 days.
Kampung Pasir Wardieburn village chief Mohammad Rizal said health
officials arrived at the village at 4 p.m. yesterday [21 Feb 2006] to
conduct a survey. "They went around asking people if they kept
chickens and if any of the birds had recently died suddenly," he
said. Mohammad said more officials descended on the village last
night to round up all the chickens in the village.
Officials and staff of the Veterinary Services Department, Kuala
Lumpur City Hall health department and Health Ministry culled 495
chickens, ducks and birds in a 5-hour operation that ended at 4 a.m.
today [22 Feb 2006].
The affected areas -- Taman Danau Kota, Pekan Danau Kota and Kampung
Belakang JPJ -- lie within a 1.5-km radius of the source of the
outbreak in Kampung Pasir Wardieburn, off Jalan Genting-Klang.
A check by the New Straits Times today [22 Feb 2006], however, found
several chickens roaming in Kampung Belakang JPJ and a squatter
village in Taman Danau Kota.
Several residents said the chickens were likely those that had
escaped the cull.
Abdul Salam Al Sahad, 65, of Taman Danau Kota said nobody was keeping
any chickens now. "I kept 10 pet birds which I had to surrender to
the health officials yesterday [21 Feb 2006]," he said.
[Byline: Devinder Singh and Dennis Wong]
--
